Source: Florida Times Union, Wed 1 May 2002 [edited
<http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/050102/met_virus.html>

Florida: West Nile Virus Confirmed in Duval County
--------------------------------------------------
Duval County's first case this year of West Nile virus was confirmed
today in a horse, prompting officials to remind residents about the
threat of the disease during active mosquito season. A 5-year-old
mare, which began displaying symptoms 2 weeks ago, became the seventh
animal in Florida to be diagnosed this year.
West Nile virus and Eastern Equine Encephalitis virus are transmitted
from birds to animals and humans by mosquitos [and sometimes cause
serious illness. In 2001, there were 66 human-related cases of
severe disease and 9 deaths, according to the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta. In Oct 2001, a 44-year-old Duval
County man became the eighth person in Florida to be diagnosed with
[West Nile virus-associated disease.
State officials urged people to consider taking precautions against
mosquito bites: avoid outdoors at dusk and dawn, wear repellents, and
eliminate standing water near homes. Officials also urged horse
owners to have their animals vaccinated against the diseases.
[Byline: P. Douglas Filaroski
