Date: Tue 23 Apr 2002
From: Duane J. Gubler <djg2@cdc.gov>

A Final Comment Regarding Incubation Period in Humans
-----------------------------------------------------
[In the ProMED-mail post "West Nile virus, incubation period in
humans: RFI 20020423.4015" Dr Manfred Green of the Israel Center for
Disease Control sought information and opinions on the duration of
the incubation period in humans. With the post "West Nile virus,
incubation period in humans (02) 20020424.4023" the thread was judged
to have been cut, but the following brief statement from Dr Duane
Gubler merits posting. - Mod.CP
Early Israeli (1950s) and French (1962) data show that the incubation
period can be as short as 3 days. We list the range as 3 to 14 days.
--
Duane J. Gubler, ScD, Director
Division of Vector-Borne Infectious Diseases
National Center for Infectious Diseases
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
P.O. Box 2087
Fort Collins CO 80522
<DGubler@cdc.gov>
